FUNCTIONALITIES OF THE INTERNAL TOOL

PRODUCT BRIEF

1. What the tool actually is
This is an internal marketing intelligence layer that sits on top of the tools the team already uses. The team keeps using Excel, Power BI, Slack, and every other tool in their stack. This tool does not touch their workflow. It plugs into the data those tools already produce.

2. Who it is for
For the Primary User: The Marketing Manager
The tool automatically connects to all ad platforms, balances out the different metrics, and flags exactly where you are losing or winning money. Instead of spending hours hunting for problems, the manager simply reviews the automated findings, approves the best strategy, and prepares for the team meeting in minutes.
For the Secondary User: The Team
The team doesn't need to log into complex software or decipher spreadsheets. The tool packages the final, manager-approved insights into a simple Slack message or a clean PDF. They instantly see what is working, what isn't, and what the plan is.

3. What it needs to work
Data connections to five platforms via their APIs — Google Ads API, Meta Marketing API, Google Analytics Data API, Mailchimp API, HubSpot API. These all exist and are well-documented. Each connection needs read-only credentials. The team does not change how they use those platforms. The tool just reads from them.
A scheduled job that runs the pull twice a week — Monday 7am before the meeting, and the last day of the month. The manager does not trigger this manually. It just happens.
A simple web interface with three screens. Screen one: this week's numbers versus last week, by channel, in a table. Screen two: the AI-generated summary — what changed, what to watch, what to consider. Screen three: the draft report, editable, with a one-click export to PDF and a copy button for Slack.
No login system needed in version one beyond a shared team password. This is internal, small team, low stakes on access control initially.

4. What would make it genuinely useful versus overcomplicated
Genuinely useful: the manager opens it Monday morning and the hard work is already done. The numbers are there. The narrative is drafted. They spend twenty minutes editing instead of two hours building. That is the job.
Overcomplicated: adding a chat interface where you can ask the tool questions, building scenario modelling for budget reallocation, creating custom alert thresholds per campaign, supporting multiple client accounts, adding user roles and permissions. All of that is version three or four — if the team actually needs it after using version one for three months.
The test for whether something belongs in version one is simple: does it directly reduce the Monday morning report-building time? If yes, it belongs. If it is solving a different problem, it does not.


AI TOOLS USED IN MANUAL STEPS
Refer: Product Scoping/architecture_1.png

Step 5: Multi-Channel KPI Comparison
Teams evaluate core channel metrics—including ROAS, CTR, conversions, and CAC—to establish a baseline of current performance across marketing platforms.
AI Agent Integration + MCP: The AI agent uses MCP-based integrations to automatically collect and normalize cross-channel marketing data, benchmark key performance metrics, and generate comparative insights that clearly identify which channels are outperforming and which are falling behind.
+ The AI agent acts like: an automated marketing analyst
It automatically:
collects data from all platforms
compares channel performance
identifies best/worst channels
prepares summarized insights
+ Role of MCP
MCP acts like: a connector bridge
It connects the AI agent with:Google Ads, Meta Ads, CRM, Analytics tools, Email tools without changing existing systems.

Step 7: Advanced Performance Analysis
Marketing analysts and managers dive deeper into the data to track trends, isolate top-performing assets, and diagnose underperforming campaigns.
AI Agent Integration: Predictive Analysis & Strategic Forecasting. The AI agent automatically calculates profit/loss margins, identifies macro trends, and delivers actionable recommendations on how to optimize current performance and where to focus future resources.
The AI agent becomes: an intelligent performance strategist
It:
analyzes trends
predicts future performance
detects problems
suggests improvements

Step 9: Agile Decision-Making & Optimization
Final strategic decisions are executed regarding budget reallocation, scaling high-performing channels, or pausing underperforming efforts.
Hybrid Integration (AI Agent + Manual Discussion): Human-in-the-Loop Execution. The AI agent generates data-driven budget scenarios and optimization roadmaps, which the team and clients review, refine, and manually approve for final deployment.
The AI agent acts like: a strategic recommendation assistant
It:
creates optimization plans
generates budget scenarios
recommends scaling strategies

Step 10: Reporting & Sharing
Marketing teams compile final reports, interactive dashboards, or presentation decks to communicate outcomes with managers, leadership, or clients.
AI Agent Integration: Automated Document Creation & Distribution. The AI agent automatically compiles performance data into polished reports, builds dynamic executive dashboards, and handles the scheduled distribution of these assets to key clients and internal stakeholders.
The AI agent acts like: a digital communications manager & graphic reporting specialist
It automatically:
compiles normalized marketing data into client-ready presentations and PDFs
builds and updates dynamic dashboards tailored to stakeholder preferences
writes executive summaries translating complex data into business impact
dispatches scheduled reports directly to managers and clients via email or communication channels


WRITTEN SPEC

In scope for v1
DATA LAYER
•	Read-only API connections to Google Ads, Meta Marketing API, Google Analytics Data API, Mailchimp API, HubSpot CRM API
•	Scheduled pull job: every Monday at 7:00am and last day of the month
•	Metric normalisation: standardise naming across platforms (e.g. 'conversions' and 'purchases' both map to a single 'conversions' field)
•	Derived metric calculation: ROAS, CAC, week-on-week delta for each KPI
•	4-week rolling average stored per metric per channel for anomaly detection
•	Sync status log: timestamp and source for every data pull, visible to the manager

AI AGENTS
•	Step 5 comparison agent: MCP-connected, pulls and compares all channels, flags anomalies above 15% deviation from rolling average
•	Step 7 analysis agent: generates 'what changed', 'issues to watch', 'options to consider' — each section rendered separately, reasoning shown inline
•	Step 9 decision agent: generates 2–3 structured options with tradeoffs after team meeting; manager selects one; decision stored with a notes field
•	Step 10 documentation agent: auto-drafts report when Step 9 decision is logged; output editable inline before export

INTERFACE — THREE SCREENS ONLY
•	Screen 1 — This week's numbers: sync status bar, 4 summary stat cards, channel comparison table with week-on-week deltas and pills
•	Screen 2 — AI analysis: three-section output from Step 7 agent; each section collapsible; manager can annotate before meeting
•	Screen 3 — Draft report: AI-generated text, editable inline, export to PDF and copy-to-Slack buttons
•	No login system in v1 — shared team access via single internal URL

OUTPUT FORMATS
•	PDF export from Screen 3
•	Copy-to-Slack button that formats the summary as plain text
•	Clean data layer accessible to existing Power BI and Looker Studio dashboards via shared read endpoint


Explicitly not in scope for v1
The following are excluded from v1. Each exclusion has a reason. None of them are permanently ruled out — they are ruled out for now because including them in v1 either increases build time without proportional value, or introduces trust risk before the team has validated the core.

Excluded feature,	Why excluded from v1
1. Budget automation / auto-execution	
Financial risk. Any wrong automated decision destroys trust in the entire tool before it has earned it. Decisions must be human-approved always.
  
2. Real-time alerts and notifications	
The team reviews weekly. Push alerts solve a problem they have not asked for yet. Adds noise before the signal is trusted.

3. Cross-channel attribution modelling	
Genuinely hard to do correctly. Doing it incorrectly makes every insight unreliable. Excluded until the team trusts simpler per-channel analysis first.
  
4. Client-facing access, login, permissions	
Clients are recipients of the output, not users of the tool. Adding access control doubles scope for zero benefit to the internal team in v1.
  
5. Historical trend analysis beyond 4 weeks	
Enough context to explain what changed this week. Deep historical analysis belongs in Power BI, which already exists.
  
6. Custom dashboard builder	
Power BI and Tableau exist and the team knows them. Pulse feeds them cleaner data. It does not replace them.
  
7. Mobile app	
The Monday morning workflow is desktop. No evidence of mobile need yet.
  
8. Multi-client or multi-workspace support	
Internal tool for one team. Generalising to multi-client is a different product.
  
9. Natural language Q&A / chat interface	
Adds complexity before core value is proven. Add after v1 if the team actually asks for it.


Success criteria for v1
Version 1 is successful if, after four weeks of Monday use, the marketing manager's pre-meeting preparation time drops from 2–3 hours to under 20 minutes, and the team reports that the AI analysis section is specific enough to use as the meeting agenda without significant rewriting.
Version 1 has failed if: numbers in Pulse do not match platform-native numbers (even once, due to attribution), the AI analysis produces vague summaries the manager has to rewrite entirely, or the team stops opening the tool after the first two weeks.

